#X text 285 443 The swing parameter is set as percentage of possible deviation. For a 60 bpm tempo and a swing value of 100% we have random values up to 100% faster or slower \, which correspond to deviationn from 60 to 120 bpm or 60 to 30 bpm., f 46;
#X obj 355 324 tempo~ 60 100;
#X obj 355 286 tgl 17 0 empty empty empty 17 7 0 10 #dfdfdf #000000 #000000 0 1;
#X text 382 282 on/off;
#X text 42 49 ELSE's [tempo] is similar to [metro] \, but with many more features \, one of which is its 'swing' parameter that makes the beats more irregular. You can check the help file for all features \, like the 'cycle' message that compensates the randomness to a cycle of \, say \, 4 beats (so even though they are irregular \, it adds up to the same amount every 4 beats)., f 83;
#X text 43 129 The [tempo] object also has a frequency multiplier parameter. It was previously shown how [metro] has a sort of frequency divider instead. Like in [metro] \, this parameter only takes effect after the next bang. If you want immediate changes use the bpm change instead. By default \, [tempo]'s unit is in bmp \, but you can change to ms. The [tempo~] object is the signal version of [tempo] and it outputs impulses instead of bangs. Again \, check their help files for more., f 83;
